[[File:Ion-Pair Chromatography.png|thumb|540x540px|Oppositely charged particles interact as they are moved through a column. While paired there is more tendency to flow through the column, in reverse phase chromatography.]]
'''Ion interaction chromatography''' (ion-pair chromatography) is a [[laboratory technique]] for separating [[Ion|ions]] with [[chromatography]]. In this technique ions are mixed with ion pairing reagents (IPR)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cecchi|first=Teresa|date=2008-08-01|title=Ion Pairing Chromatography|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/10408340802038882|journal=Critical Reviews in Analytical Chemistry|volume=38|issue=3|pages=161–213|doi=10.1080/10408340802038882|issn=1040-8347|pmid=28122458}}</ref> . The analyte combines with its reciprocal ion in the IRP, this corresponds to [[retention time]]. Often [[Organic chemistry|organic]] [[Salt (chemistry)|salts]] are selected to pair with [[Solute|solute(s)]]. The formation of this pair affects the interaction of the pair with the [[Chromatography|mobile phase and the stationary phase]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=n1zEDQAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PP1&dq=Principles+of+Instrumental+Analysis&ots=jPxMr57VDP&sig=u68mov9v_20CfDz4E3ewGBo_YBg#v=onepage&q=Principles%20of%20Instrumental%20Analysis&f=false|title=Principles of Instrumental Analysis|last=Skoog|first=Douglas A.|last2=Holler|first2=F. James|last3=Crouch|first3=Stanley R.|date=2017-01-27|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=9781305577213|language=en}}</ref>. 

